## Web Search Results

**Q5 — Prior art for threat-model-driven scanner configuration**

- **Open Threat Model (OTM)** is a platform-independent JSON spec maintained by IriusRisk (`iriusrisk/OpenThreatModel`). The associated **StartLeft** converter only transforms diverse inputs (MTMT, CloudFormation, Terraform, Terraform Plan, Visio, Draw.io, Abacus) **INTO** OTM — there is no documented OTM-to-SAST-config exporter and the OTM schema does not include CWE references in its standard fields. (https://iriusrisk.github.io/startleft/Open-Threat-Model-(OTM)/, https://github.com/iriusrisk/OpenThreatModel)
- **OWASP Threat Dragon's** TMF wiki explicitly states: *"The file format used in Threat Dragon versions 1.x and 2.x are incompatible with other open source Threat Modeling files such as pytm, Threagile and Open Threat Model."* The page lists element-mapping tables but no actual conversion utilities, and it makes **no mention of SAST integration or CWE export fields**. The TMF format has been **superseded by CycloneDX TM-BOM** (OWASP Threat Model Library project). (https://github.com/OWASP/threat-dragon/wiki/Threat-Model-File-(TMF)-format)
- **OWASP pytm** uses an internal threat-ID scheme (e.g., `INP01`, `CR01`, `AA01`) rather than CWE references. Its README documents JSON, Graphviz/DOT, PlantUML, and Markdown outputs — no Semgrep / CodeQL / Snyk integration is described, and CWE export is not part of the threat output. (https://github.com/OWASP/pytm)
- **Semgrep registry metadata** is annotated with CWE and OWASP tags when applicable — this is a documented feature ("Security rules in the Semgrep Registry are annotated with CWE and OWASP metadata when applicable"), so the *consumer* side of a CWE→rule lookup is feasible against the registry. (Search snippet from `semgrep.dev/blog/...` and `github.com/semgrep/semgrep`)
- **Adjacent commercial tooling** that surfaced: Phoenix Security's Semgrep integration is an ASPM correlation/enrichment layer over scan output, not a threat-model-driven config generator. (https://phoenix.security/phoenix-security-integration-semgrep/)
- **Academic angle:** "Semgrep*: Improving the Limited Performance of Static Application Security Testing (SAST) Tools" (EASE 2024) focuses on hand-authored rule additions to Semgrep that lifted detection by 181%, not on threat-model-driven rule selection. (https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/3661167.3661262)
- **Verdict signal:** Across the three searches, **no published OTM-or-similar → Semgrep config converter** appeared, and the dominant interop story in the threat-modeling community is moving toward **CycloneDX TM-BOM** as a common exchange format rather than scanner-config generation. The "threat-model edit → ruleset re-derivation" loop appears to be **null prior art** in the OSS space at this search depth.

**Q3 — Audit shape for PCI DSS 6.3.2 and SOC 2 CC7.1**

- The search returned generic PCI DSS 4.0 and SOC 2 overview/checklist content; **no primary source surfaced specific guidance on SARIF as an accepted evidence format, retention windows for SAST artifacts (1/3/7 years), or the documented pattern for risk-accepted findings**. PCI DSS v4.0 became effective in March 2025 with several future-dated requirements activating April 1, 2025, per a GuidePoint summary. (https://www.guidepointsecurity.com/blog/pci-dss-4-0-major-future-dated-requirements/, https://linfordco.com/blog/pci-dss-4-0-requirements-guide/)
- SOC 2 audit guides recommend automating CI/CD to include SAST/DAST but did not, in this search slice, specify the artifact-format expectations auditors accept. (https://soc2auditors.org/insights/soc-2-audit-checklist/)
- **Conclusion:** the Q3 slice in this search budget is **inconclusive on the audit-format specifics**. A follow-up targeted search against PCI SSC's document library, AICPA TSC 2017+2022, and QSA-firm blog posts (Coalfire / Schellman / A-LIGN) is needed before the v1 capture-format decision can be defended.

