## Web Search Results

### Q1 — Semgrep CI integration patterns and baseline mechanics

- `SEMGREP_BASELINE_REF` is **not** the recommended switch on GitHub Actions / GitLab CI — `semgrep ci` auto-detects diff scope from the GitHub PR event, so the env var is only meaningful for "other" CI providers. Source: Semgrep CI environment variables docs (https://semgrep.dev/docs/semgrep-ci/ci-environment-variables) and Semgrep CI configuration reference (https://semgrep.dev/docs/semgrep-ci/configuration-reference/).
- Semgrep's documented OSS pattern is: a **scheduled full scan on default branch** (nightly/weekly) plus a **diff-aware PR scan** that only blocks on newly introduced findings — explicitly designed so existing findings don't gate every PR. Source: https://semgrep.dev/docs/semgrep-ci/findings-ci and https://semgrep.dev/docs/deployment/oss-deployment.
- Sample Actions YAML and "minimum viable" recipes are published on Semgrep's "Sample CI configurations" and the j3ssie/sample-semgrep-ci reference repo. Sources: https://semgrep.dev/docs/semgrep-ci/sample-ci-configs, https://github.com/j3ssie/sample-semgrep-ci.
- A common pitfall called out in Semgrep's KB is git command failures during PR/MR scans (shallow checkouts, missing base ref) — fix is `fetch-depth: 0` on actions/checkout. Source: https://semgrep.dev/docs/kb/semgrep-ci/git-command-errors.
- `0xdbe.github.io` walks through enabling Semgrep code scanning end-to-end including SARIF upload to GitHub code scanning UI as the OSS-only PR-comment alternative. Source: https://0xdbe.github.io/GitHub-HowToEnableCodeScanningWithSemgrep/.

### Q2 — CWE → Semgrep rule pack mapping

- Semgrep maintains curated rule packs `p/owasp-top-ten` and `p/cwe-top-25` and re-mapped **all 4,000+ rules** to OWASP Top 10:2025 categories so the metadata is now coherent against the latest taxonomy. Sources: https://semgrep.dev/blog/2026/owasp-top-10-2025-whats-new/, https://semgrep.dev/p/owasp-top-ten, https://semgrep.dev/p/cwe-top-25.
- Per the contributor guide, every rule is expected to carry a CWE in its metadata (`metadata.cwe`) — implies the field is populated as a norm, not aspirationally. Source: https://semgrep.dev/docs/contributing/contributing-to-semgrep-rules-repository.
- New JS/TS rules covering OWASP Top 10 + Express/NestJS/Hapi/Koa shipped in the default ruleset (Feb 2025). Source: https://semgrep.dev/docs/release-notes/february-2025.
- The semgrep-rules monorepo is the authoritative YAML source — the metadata field is greppable across the registry. Source: https://github.com/semgrep/semgrep-rules.
- The searches did **not** turn up an external "CWE → Semgrep pack" lookup table maintained by MITRE, OWASP, or third parties; coverage queries appear to require either the Semgrep registry UI/API or grepping the rules repo.

### Q3 — PCI DSS 6.3.2 and SOC 2 CC7.1 SAST evidence

- Search returned mostly **generic** PCI DSS 4.0 / SOC 2 readiness material — no source explicitly stated SARIF format, retention windows, or documented audit-failure patterns for "mapped-but-not-scanned" CWE coverage claims. Sources scanned: https://www.pcisecuritystandards.org/document_library/, https://linfordco.com/blog/pci-dss-4-0-requirements-guide/, https://soc2auditors.org/insights/soc-2-audit-checklist/, https://www.dsalta.com/resources/articles/soc-2-compliance-in-2025-requirements-readiness-and-audit-success.
- Confirmed signal: PCI DSS v4.0 future-dated requirements (best-practice until 31 March 2025) became mandatory thereafter; SAST/DAST automation in CI is generally accepted as evidence for SOC 2 CC7.1, but specifics (schema, retention) are auditor-dependent. Source: https://linfordco.com/blog/pci-dss-4-0-requirements-guide/, https://www.strikegraph.com/blog/pci-dss-vs-soc-2.
- **Verdict for synthesis:** this question is under-served by web search; primary sources (PCI Council 6.3.2 supplemental guidance PDF, AICPA TSC 2017/2022) need to be read directly. NIST SSDF SP 800-218 PW.7 was not surfaced in the search.

### Q4 — `pull_request_target` security posture

- GitHub announced 2025-11-07 changelog: from **2025-12-08**, `pull_request_target` workflow file + checkout commit are forced to come from the default branch, eliminating a class of "old-branch vulnerable workflow" attacks. Source: https://github.blog/changelog/2025-11-07-actions-pull_request_target-and-environment-branch-protections-changes/.
- High-severity 2025 incidents reinforcing "use `pull_request` unless you genuinely need fork-secret access":
  - **Shai Hulud v2** (Nov 2025) — self-replicating worm via `pull_request_target` abuse, ~20k repos affected. Source: (cited in Wiz blog) https://www.wiz.io/blog/github-actions-security-guide.
  - **tj-actions/changed-files** compromise (Mar 2025), CVE-2025-30066. Source: https://github.com/advisories/ghsa-mrrh-fwg8-r2c3.
  - **CVE-2025-61671** — Microsoft `pull_request_target` advisory, CVSS 9.3.
- GitHub Security Lab's canonical "preventing pwn requests" guidance: prefer `pull_request`; if `pull_request_target` is required, never check out the PR head, restrict `permissions:` to least-privilege, and split into **two-workflow patterns** (untrusted analysis on `pull_request` → trusted comment-poster on `workflow_run`). Sources: https://securitylab.github.com/resources/github-actions-preventing-pwn-requests/, https://www.wiz.io/blog/github-actions-security-guide, https://orca.security/resources/blog/pull-request-nightmare-part-2-exploits/.
- Sysdig surfaced concrete misconfigured workflows in MITRE / Splunk OSS repos as recently as 2025 — the failure mode is widespread, not theoretical. Source: https://www.sysdig.com/blog/insecure-github-actions-found-in-mitre-splunk-and-other-open-source-repositories.

### Q5 — Threat-model-driven scanner configuration prior art

- **No direct competitor surfaced.** No published OTM-or-similar → Semgrep config converter was found in the searches.
- Closest adjacent prior art: AppSec Untangled "Threat Modeling Handbook #5" — manually wires a threat model into custom Semgrep rules in CI as a discipline, not an automated pipeline. Source: https://medium.com/appsec-untangled/threat-modeling-handbook-5-convert-your-threat-model-into-an-automated-pentest-using-devsecops-84efcd138202.
- **Standardisation in flight:** OWASP Threat Dragon and pytm both participate in the CycloneDX **TM-BOM** (Threat Model Bill of Materials) effort to unify formats — but their current file formats are incompatible with each other and with OTM/Threagile. So a "read the threat model, derive the ruleset" loop has no canonical input format yet. Source: https://threatmodeling.dev/dragpyt/.
- pytm is the most "code-as-threat-model" of the bunch and could in principle export CWE lists programmatically. Source: https://github.com/OWASP/pytm, https://owasp.org/www-project-pytm/.
- Verdict for synthesis: **the wedge appears unoccupied**. No vendor (Snyk Code, GHAS CodeQL config, Checkmarx One presets, Veracode policy) was returned by these queries as offering threat-model-driven *re-derivation*; they offer manual policy/config files.

