## Web Search Results

**Q1 — Semgrep CI integration patterns and baseline mechanics**
- The official Semgrep CI deployment doc explicitly notes that the `SEMGREP_BASELINE_REF` env var **does not apply** to GitHub Actions or GitLab CI/CD; on those platforms `semgrep ci` automatically performs diff-aware scans on pull requests by comparing against the merge base. ([Add Semgrep to CI/CD](https://semgrep.dev/docs/deployment/add-semgrep-to-ci))
- Recommended pattern for adoption on a repo with significant pre-existing findings is split workflows: one full-scan job on the default branch and one diff-aware job on `pull_request`, so adoption does not require fixing all legacy findings up front. ([Add Semgrep to CI/CD](https://semgrep.dev/docs/deployment/add-semgrep-to-ci), [Sample CI configurations](https://semgrep.dev/docs/semgrep-ci/sample-ci-configs))
- Semgrep maintains a "Findings in CI" reference covering blocking severity behavior, and a CI configuration reference page; both are the canonical citation surfaces for severity gating. ([Findings in CI](https://semgrep.dev/docs/semgrep-ci/findings-ci), [CI configuration reference](https://semgrep.dev/docs/semgrep-ci/configuration-reference/))
- A community walkthrough shows how to wire Semgrep into GitHub Code Scanning via SARIF upload as an OSS-only path (no Semgrep AppSec Platform required). ([GitHub: How To Enable Code Scanning With Semgrep](https://0xdbe.github.io/GitHub-HowToEnableCodeScanningWithSemgrep/))
- The fetched docs page did **not** name `--baseline-ref`, `--severity`, or `--config` flags directly — only the env-var form `SEMGREP_BASELINE_REF`. The CLI configuration reference exists but was not exhaustively crawled in this slice.

**Q2 — CWE → Semgrep rule pack mapping**
- This slice was not directly searched. Adjacent results indicate Semgrep registry rules carry CWE/OWASP metadata ("Rules include relevant CWE and OWASP categories…enrich rules with metadata like CWE identifiers"), but no source confirmed coverage completeness, queryable index endpoints, or per-language gap analysis. ([RealVuln benchmarking paper](https://arxiv.org/html/2604.13764), [DevOps Daily Semgrep guide](https://devops-daily.com/guides/sast-tools/03-semgrep)) Verdict on canonical-vs-author-our-own remains unresolved here.

