**Q4 — `pull_request_target` security posture and safe defaults**
- A material GitHub change is rolling out **December 8, 2025**: `pull_request_target` now always uses the **default branch** as the workflow source and checkout commit, regardless of the PR base. `GITHUB_REF` resolves to the default branch and `GITHUB_SHA` to its latest commit. Closes the historical exploit class where outdated workflows on non-default branches were re-triggerable. ([GitHub Changelog 2025-11-07](https://github.blog/changelog/2025-11-07-actions-pull_request_target-and-environment-branch-protections-changes/))
- GitHub's explicit guidance: prefer `pull_request` when elevated permissions are not required; if `pull_request_target` is used, configure default token permissions to read-only or apply least-privilege in the workflow `permissions:` block. ([GitHub Changelog 2025-11-07](https://github.blog/changelog/2025-11-07-actions-pull_request_target-and-environment-branch-protections-changes/))
- GitHub Security Lab's "Preventing pwn requests" remains the canonical write-up of the attack class and is still being updated with new vulnerability patterns and mitigations in 2025. ([Preventing pwn requests](https://securitylab.github.com/resources/github-actions-preventing-pwn-requests/), [New patterns and mitigations](https://securitylab.github.com/resources/github-actions-new-patterns-and-mitigations/))
- Independent hardening guides from Wiz, Sysdig, Orca, and AquilaX corroborate the least-privilege + default-deny `permissions:` recommendation and warn about misconfig prevalence in OSS repos (Sysdig: MITRE/Splunk among observed cases). ([Wiz](https://www.wiz.io/blog/github-actions-security-guide), [Sysdig](https://www.sysdig.com/blog/insecure-github-actions-found-in-mitre-splunk-and-other-open-source-repositories), [Orca](https://orca.security/resources/blog/github-actions-security-risks/), [AquilaX](https://aquilax.ai/blog/github-actions-security-hardening))
- GitHub's 2026 Actions security roadmap signals further default-hardening and policy/observability controls are coming. ([2026 Actions security roadmap](https://github.blog/news-insights/product-news/whats-coming-to-our-github-actions-2026-security-roadmap/))

**Q5 — Prior art for threat-model-driven scanner configuration**
- **OTM (Open Threat Model)** is a platform-independent JSON schema, current version **0.2.0** (released **2023-08-30**), maintained by IriusRisk. The repo's documentation does **not** mention Semgrep, SAST tooling, or any documented OTM-to-scanner-config converter. ([iriusrisk/OpenThreatModel](https://github.com/iriusrisk/OpenThreatModel))
- A 2023 AppSec Untangled article ("Threat Modeling Handbook #5") sketches the manual pattern of converting a threat model to automated SAST checks via Semgrep custom rules, but treats it as advisory practice — not a packaged tool. ([Threat Modeling Handbook #5](https://medium.com/appsec-untangled/threat-modeling-handbook-5-convert-your-threat-model-into-an-automated-pentest-using-devsecops-84efcd138202))
- **Autogrep** (Lambda Security) automates Semgrep rule *generation* from CVE patches using LLMs — orthogonal to threat-model-driven *selection*, but the closest published prior art on automated Semgrep config. ([Autogrep](https://lambdasec.github.io/AutoGrep-Automated-Generation-and-Filtering-of-Semgrep-Rules-from-Vulnerability-Patches/))
- GitLab's SAST customization docs allow project-level rule overrides but do not consume a threat model. ([GitLab Customize rulesets](https://docs.gitlab.com/user/application_security/sast/customize_rulesets/))
- Two community Claude/Agent skills already exist for "wire Semgrep into a project" (`sast-semgrep`, `claude-build-workflow-sast-semgrep`) — adjacent prior art, but neither is threat-model-driven. ([sast-semgrep skill](https://claude-plugins.dev/skills/@AgentSecOps/SecOpsAgentKit/sast-semgrep), [Lobehub skill listing](https://lobehub.com/skills/rohunj-claude-build-workflow-sast-semgrep))
