## Web Search Results

### Q1 — Semgrep CI integration patterns and baseline mechanics

- `SEMGREP_BASELINE_REF` is **not** the recommended knob on GitHub Actions or GitLab CI/CD — `semgrep ci` auto-detects the merge-base from the PR event payload, so the env var is reserved for "other" CI providers (Jenkins, CircleCI, Buildkite). Source: Semgrep CI configuration reference / sample CI configs pages (https://semgrep.dev/docs/semgrep-ci/configuration-reference/, https://semgrep.dev/docs/semgrep-ci/sample-ci-configs).
- The fetch-depth knob that *does* matter on GitHub Actions is `SEMGREP_GHA_MIN_FETCH_DEPTH`; Semgrep recommends raising it on repos with deep PR histories so the merge-base computation doesn't fall off the shallow clone (https://semgrep.dev/docs/semgrep-ci/ci-environment-variables).
- Recommended pattern for noisy existing repos: schedule a full scan on `main` with a broad pack (e.g. `p/default`), and run a tighter, higher-precision rule pack on PRs in diff-aware mode (https://semgrep.dev/docs/deployment/add-semgrep-to-ci, https://appsec.guide/docs/static-analysis/semgrep/continuous-integration/).
- Trail of Bits' Testing Handbook ("Continuous integration") is a current third-party long-form guide for Semgrep-on-GitHub-Actions hardening recipes (https://appsec.guide/docs/static-analysis/semgrep/continuous-integration/).
- Documented common pitfall: PR/merge-request scans hit "failed to run a git command" errors when the runner's shallow clone can't reach the merge-base — fix is increasing fetch depth or using `actions/checkout@v4` with `fetch-depth: 0` (https://semgrep.dev/docs/kb/semgrep-ci/git-command-errors).

### Q2 — CWE → Semgrep rule pack mapping

- Search did not surface a canonical CWE-indexed registry endpoint; the Semgrep contributing guide confirms each rule *can* carry a `metadata.cwe` field but treats it as advisory metadata, not a queryable pivot ("Include the appropriate CWE … as CWE can explain what vulnerability your rule is trying to find") (https://semgrep.dev/docs/contributing/contributing-to-semgrep-rules-repository).
- No third-party "CWE → Semgrep pack" mapping document or paper surfaced in this slice — verdict on coverage completeness is **inconclusive from web search alone** and likely requires direct API/YAML inspection of `p/owasp-top-10`, `p/cwe-top-25`, and `p/security-audit` packs.
- A `github-actions` ruleset exists separately (https://semgrep.dev/p/github-actions) and is what most "scan workflow YAML for tj-actions-style issues" guides reference.

### Q3 — Audit evidence for PCI DSS 6.3.2 / SOC 2 CC7.1

- Not searched in this slice (3-query budget). Flagging as a gap for a follow-up search phase; questions about SARIF retention, "addressed" definitions, and risk-acceptance memos remain unanswered here.

### Q4 — `pull_request_target` security posture and safe defaults

- **Material 2025 change**: GitHub announced (changelog 2025-11-07, effective 2025-12-08) that `pull_request_target` now always loads the workflow file and checkout ref from the **default branch**, regardless of the PR's base branch — closing a class of "outdated workflow on a stale base branch is still exploitable" attacks (https://github.blog/changelog/2025-11-07-actions-pull_request_target-and-environment-branch-protections-changes/).
- GitHub Security Lab's canonical "Preventing pwn requests" guidance is still the primary doc for the `pull_request` vs `pull_request_target` decision and the "two-workflow split" pattern (analysis runs on `pull_request` with no secrets; comment-poster runs on `workflow_run` with elevated perms) (https://securitylab.github.com/resources/github-actions-preventing-pwn-requests/).
- **March 2025 tj-actions incident** is the current canonical case study for cascading workflow compromise — referenced by both Wiz and Orca's hardening guides (https://www.wiz.io/blog/github-actions-security-guide, https://orca.security/resources/blog/github-actions-hardening/).
- Sysdig's 2024 audit of MITRE / Splunk / other OSS repos documents real-world `pull_request_target` misconfigurations and is a useful "what bad looks like" reference (https://www.sysdig.com/blog/insecure-github-actions-found-in-mitre-splunk-and-other-open-source-repositories).
- Hardening posture recommended across sources: top-level `permissions: read-all` (or empty `{}`), explicit per-job `permissions:` blocks with the minimum needed (`contents: read`, `security-events: write` only on the SARIF-upload job), pin actions by SHA, never use `pull_request_target` for SAST unless cross-fork PR comment posting genuinely requires it (https://www.wiz.io/blog/github-actions-security-guide, https://aquilax.ai/blog/github-actions-security-hardening, https://arctiq.com/blog/top-10-github-actions-security-pitfalls-the-ultimate-guide-to-bulletproof-workflows).

### Q5 — Prior art for threat-model-driven scanner configuration

- **OWASP pytm** generates DFDs, sequence diagrams, and threat lists, but search did not surface a built-in CWE-export-to-Semgrep adapter (https://github.com/OWASP/pytm, https://owasp.org/www-project-pytm/).
- **OWASP Ontology-driven Threat Modeling Framework (OdTM)** exists as a related ontological approach but no Semgrep bridge surfaced (https://owasp.org/www-project-ontology-driven-threat-modeling-framework/).
- **SecOpsTM** (ellipse2v/SecOpsTM) is an adjacent 2024–2026-era project doing STRIDE-as-code with MITRE ATT&CK / D3FEND / CAPEC mapping and CI/CD-ready report output — closest published prior art in the "threat model → automated security artifact" space, but its outputs are reports/Navigator layers, not Semgrep configs (https://github.com/ellipse2v/SecOpsTM).
- O'Reilly *Threat Modeling* Ch. 4 ("Automated Threat Modeling") frames the problem space but no specific OTM→Semgrep tool was returned (https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/threat-modeling/9781492056546/ch04.html).
- **Verdict (preliminary)**: no direct competitor surfaced in this 1-query slice. SecOpsTM is the closest adjacent player and could pivot into this space; OWASP Threat Dragon's OTM JSON was not directly evaluated here and is worth a targeted follow-up search.

